sec.p:
First in Russia, where they are all written in modified forms of Cyrillic script:


Yakut, a Turkic language of eastern Siberia (Acts checked in September 1995, New Testament published 2004);

Kalmyk, an Altaic language of the Mongolian subdivision spoken west of the Caspian Sea (Acts checked in November 1996, New Testament published 2002);

Chechen, a North Caucasian language spoken in the Caucasus (Acts checked in May 2001, New Testament published 2007);

Khakas, a Turkic language of southern Siberia (Acts checked in October 2006, New Testament published 2009).
